20
00:00:43,711 --> 00:00:50,295
[SPEAKER_03]: There will be a meeting of the Medford City Council Committee of the Whole on Wednesday, December 14th, 2022 at 6 p.m.

21
00:00:50,755 --> 00:00:53,297
[SPEAKER_03]: in the Medford City Council Chambers and via Zoom.

22
00:00:53,697 --> 00:01:02,502
[SPEAKER_03]: The purpose of the meeting is to address outstanding questions from the recently completed zoning recodification and to set a fee schedule for the plan development district proposals, paper 22-533 and paper 22-581.

23
00:01:05,803 --> 00:01:14,370
[SPEAKER_03]: The City Council has invited Building Commissioner Bill Forti, Planning Development and Sustainability Director Alicia Hunt, and Economic Development Director Victor Schrader to attend this meeting.

24
00:01:14,550 --> 00:01:20,174
[SPEAKER_03]: For further information, aides on accommodations, contact the City Clerk at 781-393-2425.

25
00:01:20,354 --> 00:01:22,756
[SPEAKER_03]: Sincerely yours, Nicole Murrell, Council President.

26
00:01:23,357 --> 00:01:32,423
[SPEAKER_03]: So as the meeting notice states, we are here tonight to talk through perhaps some scrivener's errors and some portions of the zoning recodification that was passed back in March.

27
00:01:33,484 --> 00:01:34,465
[SPEAKER_03]: Some portions of it that may be

28
00:01:34,959 --> 00:01:39,841
[SPEAKER_03]: for interpretation that we may need to take a further look at and actually vote for some zoning changes to update that.

29
00:01:40,461 --> 00:01:51,326
[SPEAKER_03]: Scribner errors, if we were to address them, don't actually count as voting, as zoning changes as they were errors in copying or transitioning the document from one format to another.

30
00:01:52,266 --> 00:01:57,889
[SPEAKER_03]: We also have the discussion around setting up the schedule for the planned development district proposals.

31
00:01:57,969 --> 00:02:01,190
[SPEAKER_03]: That is something that was added in the zoning reclassification

32
00:02:02,388 --> 00:02:10,076
[SPEAKER_03]: package and for these proposals there's a fee that we can charge and looking to have a brief discussion on what that fee should be.

33
00:02:11,097 --> 00:02:19,705
[SPEAKER_03]: So I'm happy to hand over to any councilors who'd like to speak first or go right to Planning Development and Sustainability Director Hunt going to Vice President Behrs.

34
00:02:19,885 --> 00:02:20,686
[SPEAKER_08]: Thank you Madam President.

35
00:02:21,026 --> 00:02:22,087
[SPEAKER_08]: Thank you everyone for being here tonight.

36
00:02:23,068 --> 00:02:26,011
[SPEAKER_08]: Thank you for outlining all the stuff that we have to look at.

37
00:02:27,413 --> 00:02:33,575
[SPEAKER_08]: If we could, I think maybe a three part approach from easiest to hardest might be the best way to go about it.

38
00:02:34,555 --> 00:02:41,657
[SPEAKER_08]: If we could start and look at the PDD fee, I know that Victor said that that would be actually, we could put that in the council rules.

39
00:02:41,737 --> 00:02:44,138
[SPEAKER_08]: So it wouldn't need to go through like a zoning process.

40
00:02:44,158 --> 00:02:46,378
[SPEAKER_08]: It's already authorized by the zoning ordinance.

41
00:02:46,858 --> 00:02:50,719
[SPEAKER_08]: Then look at the Scribner's errors and just get us all on the same page about what we need to do from there.

42
00:02:50,879 --> 00:02:56,761
[SPEAKER_08]: And then the bigger piece, which will outlive this meeting would be, you know, substantive changes requiring a vote under

43
00:02:57,346 --> 00:03:00,008
[SPEAKER_08]: the zoning laws, so that would be my preference.

44
00:03:01,449 --> 00:03:02,270
[SPEAKER_03]: I think that makes sense.

45
00:03:02,290 --> 00:03:05,633
[SPEAKER_03]: Is anyone opposed to that approach?

46
00:03:05,673 --> 00:03:13,119
[SPEAKER_03]: So first to talk about those PDD fees, Victor or Alicia, would you like to talk about that?

47
00:03:13,159 --> 00:03:13,660
[SPEAKER_12]: Give you a moment.

48
00:03:18,043 --> 00:03:19,044
[SPEAKER_10]: Good evening, Councillors.

49
00:03:19,184 --> 00:03:22,627
[SPEAKER_10]: Victor Schrader, Economic Development Director for the City of Medford.

50
00:03:24,627 --> 00:03:27,411
[SPEAKER_10]: Yeah, I guess, where would you like to start, President Morrell?

51
00:03:28,032 --> 00:03:31,277
[SPEAKER_10]: I provided you with some examples from similar communities.

52
00:03:31,297 --> 00:03:35,343
[SPEAKER_03]: I think the thing to keep- Yeah, if you want to just talk through a few of those examples, I can pull them up as well.

53
00:03:35,835 --> 00:03:40,378
[SPEAKER_10]: And I think the thing to keep in mind is the planned development districts are a new tool in Medford.

54
00:03:40,398 --> 00:03:43,600
[SPEAKER_10]: They are pretty common statewide and across the country.

55
00:03:44,581 --> 00:03:49,164
[SPEAKER_10]: Here in Medford, there's no minimum size, lot size for the PDD.

56
00:03:49,204 --> 00:03:51,185
[SPEAKER_10]: So we could see a range of projects.

57
00:03:51,806 --> 00:03:57,729
[SPEAKER_10]: Currently, we're considering a planned development district that totals about a million square feet.

58
00:03:58,930 --> 00:04:02,092
[SPEAKER_10]: And then another that's residential, that's about 60,000 square feet.

59
00:04:03,769 --> 00:04:17,535
[SPEAKER_10]: So as you would imagine, the million square feet proposal takes quite a bit more time and attention from staff and from council to work through than the smaller project.

60
00:04:17,615 --> 00:04:26,479
[SPEAKER_10]: But I would liken these reviews to the site plan review process in the end.

61
00:04:27,017 --> 00:04:31,360
[SPEAKER_10]: Council will be approving a zoning amendment for the planned development districts.

62
00:04:31,921 --> 00:04:45,451
[SPEAKER_10]: So it might not be in the same level of detail as a site plan review, but you're going to be looking through plans and taking the time to understand what a development proposal is and how it'll impact the community.

63
00:04:49,854 --> 00:04:54,518
[SPEAKER_03]: And just to build on that, just for folks who, as you said, it's new.

64
00:04:54,905 --> 00:05:03,372
[SPEAKER_03]: folks unfamiliar, the very simple form of this is basically someone coming to us with a project and saying, hey, you're not zoned for this, but here's what I would like to do in this space, correct?

65
00:05:03,812 --> 00:05:04,693
[SPEAKER_10]: Exactly, yeah.

66
00:05:05,734 --> 00:05:11,038
[SPEAKER_10]: And so the first step is to propose a zoning amendment, and that's what the plan development district is.

67
00:05:11,959 --> 00:05:22,668
[SPEAKER_10]: If the project is large enough, when they're moving towards permitting, it will have to go through a typical zoning process, but the zoning for the project will be established under the

68
00:05:23,312 --> 00:05:27,355
[SPEAKER_10]: the plan development district, which acts as an overlay.

69
00:05:28,716 --> 00:05:47,751
[SPEAKER_10]: Another thing to consider as you're weighing these potential fees is that we think these projects are good candidates for peer review, which is allowed under 53G, which is through the state code.

70
00:05:50,207 --> 00:06:11,867
[SPEAKER_10]: The initial project we're reviewing now, we will be recommending to the CD community development board and council that an attorney come on to help out with the drafting of the ordinance language, just to make sure that it's responding to what the developer would like, but also is in accordance with our rules.

71
00:06:12,579 --> 00:06:22,661
[SPEAKER_10]: So that's 53G allows municipalities to hire peer review consultants at the expense of the applicant.

72
00:06:23,301 --> 00:06:25,302
[SPEAKER_10]: So those wouldn't be expenses that we would incur.

73
00:06:25,322 --> 00:06:28,102
[SPEAKER_03]: Vice President Behrs.

74
00:06:28,402 --> 00:06:29,203
[SPEAKER_08]: Thank you, Madam President.

75
00:06:29,583 --> 00:06:30,963
[SPEAKER_08]: Thank you, Victor.

76
00:06:32,183 --> 00:06:39,005
[SPEAKER_08]: In the examples you sent over, one of them was the 5 cents per, was it 5 cents per 5,000 square feet?

77
00:06:41,521 --> 00:06:42,762
[SPEAKER_03]: 5 cents per square foot.

78
00:06:42,962 --> 00:06:44,203
[SPEAKER_08]: 5 cents per square foot above 5,000.

79
00:06:44,543 --> 00:06:45,004
[SPEAKER_08]: Sorry.

80
00:06:45,664 --> 00:06:47,185
[SPEAKER_03]: And that's for site plan review.

81
00:06:47,345 --> 00:06:47,546
[SPEAKER_08]: Right.

82
00:06:47,706 --> 00:06:49,767
[SPEAKER_08]: Do you think, I mean, so that would be variable.

83
00:06:49,787 --> 00:06:53,009
[SPEAKER_08]: It would, you know, we'd have a higher fee relative to the size.

84
00:06:54,270 --> 00:07:02,456
[SPEAKER_08]: Do you think that if we went with that number plus the, you know, is there something that you think we should include in the council rules around 53G?

85
00:07:02,956 --> 00:07:09,200
[SPEAKER_08]: Just to say we will, you know, basically should the rule be, here's we're setting the fee at 5 cents per.

86
00:07:09,220 --> 00:07:10,121
[SPEAKER_08]: Yes.

87
00:07:10,646 --> 00:07:17,554
[SPEAKER_08]: square foot above 5,000, and in cases where 53G applies, we recommend its use or something like that.

88
00:07:17,594 --> 00:07:20,917
[SPEAKER_08]: Is that kind of what you're getting at, or should we not mention 53G at all?

89
00:07:23,960 --> 00:07:28,005
[SPEAKER_10]: I don't know how it would be applied to the council rules, necessarily.

90
00:07:28,325 --> 00:07:31,208
[SPEAKER_10]: It's allowed under our current ordinances.

91
00:07:31,389 --> 00:07:31,629
[SPEAKER_10]: Right.

92
00:07:33,535 --> 00:07:35,016
[SPEAKER_10]: I'm not sure that that's necessary.

93
00:07:35,036 --> 00:07:38,637
[SPEAKER_10]: I think that might be maybe something to think about further.

94
00:07:38,697 --> 00:07:43,259
[SPEAKER_10]: I haven't looked into that myself, so I'm not sure I'm in a position to give you guidance on that.

95
00:07:43,479 --> 00:07:43,779
[SPEAKER_08]: That's fine.

96
00:07:44,519 --> 00:07:52,742
[SPEAKER_08]: In your office's position, would setting it as the same fee as site plan review be onerous, or would that be acceptable?

97
00:07:56,348 --> 00:07:59,551
[SPEAKER_10]: That seems in line with some of our peer communities.

98
00:07:59,851 --> 00:08:07,797
[SPEAKER_10]: I was looking at Somerville's master plan special permits, $0.02 per new gross square foot.

99
00:08:11,120 --> 00:08:20,647
[SPEAKER_10]: Ours is a little higher, but they both seem to be in line.

100
00:08:22,105 --> 00:08:25,049
[SPEAKER_10]: graduating fees, which I think is probably the right approach.

101
00:08:25,349 --> 00:08:33,680
[SPEAKER_05]: Sorry, I apologize for interrupting Alicia Hunt, Planning Director.

102
00:08:34,621 --> 00:08:37,985
[SPEAKER_05]: We were just consulting because the CD board recently adopted 53G.

103
00:08:41,026 --> 00:08:42,587
[SPEAKER_05]: We searched our ordinances just now.

104
00:08:42,727 --> 00:08:46,230
[SPEAKER_05]: It is in our ordinances under the Conservation Commission.

105
00:08:46,250 --> 00:08:47,711
[SPEAKER_05]: Wetlands has adopted it.

106
00:08:48,091 --> 00:08:51,874
[SPEAKER_05]: The CD board adopted it as part of their rules and regulations.

107
00:08:52,575 --> 00:09:05,904
[SPEAKER_05]: So in lieu of consulting a lawyer at this moment, I would say that the city council probably should take the language that the CD board adopted because that was prepared for us by legal counsel.

108
00:09:07,585 --> 00:09:12,746
[SPEAKER_05]: and actually it was prepared by Jonathan Silverstein, who is now a partner with Mark Bobrowski.

109
00:09:14,466 --> 00:09:25,768
[SPEAKER_05]: We use the language that he gave us and adopted it, and that the city council probably ought to perhaps check with Attorney Silverstein, but adopt that language as well to be proper.

110
00:09:26,348 --> 00:09:28,349
[SPEAKER_05]: So sorry to interrupt and contradict you.

111
00:09:28,389 --> 00:09:30,109
[SPEAKER_05]: I just wanted to make sure you had that.

112
00:09:30,129 --> 00:09:32,129
[SPEAKER_05]: Thank you.

113
00:09:32,309 --> 00:09:32,869
[SPEAKER_10]: Great, thank you.

114
00:09:34,430 --> 00:09:35,330
[SPEAKER_10]: No contradiction there.

115
00:09:38,073 --> 00:09:38,453
[SPEAKER_10]: Are you all set?

116
00:09:39,074 --> 00:09:43,738
[SPEAKER_08]: Yeah, I'll wait for the councillors, but I'll make a motion after everyone's had a chance to speak on this.

117
00:09:45,359 --> 00:09:47,161
[SPEAKER_09]: Any other councillors wish to speak?

118
00:09:47,201 --> 00:09:47,701
[SPEAKER_09]: Councilor Collins?

119
00:09:48,242 --> 00:09:48,982
[SPEAKER_09]: Yeah, thank you.

120
00:09:49,042 --> 00:09:50,003
[SPEAKER_09]: Nothing substantive to add.

121
00:09:50,023 --> 00:09:51,644
[SPEAKER_09]: I think that's why we're having this discussion.

122
00:09:51,684 --> 00:09:57,609
[SPEAKER_09]: I think this is a reasonable thing to, excuse me, reasonable thing to add into this process.

123
00:09:57,629 --> 00:10:04,295
[SPEAKER_09]: I appreciate hearing about context from neighboring communities would make sure that our fee standards are

124
00:10:05,448 --> 00:10:09,191
[SPEAKER_09]: in line and kind of create a consistent experience for developers in the area.

125
00:10:09,211 --> 00:10:15,276
[SPEAKER_12]: Any councilors on Zoom wish to speak at this time?

126
00:10:16,757 --> 00:10:17,258
[SPEAKER_06]: If I can.

127
00:10:17,418 --> 00:10:19,159
[SPEAKER_06]: Please.

128
00:10:22,682 --> 00:10:32,990
[SPEAKER_06]: I'm excited that we've been looking at this process and moving forward, but again, I think anything we do would adhere on the side of caution without legal representation.

129
00:10:33,691 --> 00:10:34,492
[SPEAKER_06]: I appreciate that.

130
00:10:35,802 --> 00:10:39,606
[SPEAKER_06]: Someone has already done something for another body, but it's not our body.

131
00:10:41,027 --> 00:10:50,236
[SPEAKER_06]: So I think that, you know, I wouldn't, I wouldn't proceed in recommending anything until we have a city solicitor look at it.

132
00:10:53,159 --> 00:10:57,884
[SPEAKER_06]: This is, this is where I find myself in a conundrum when it comes to, um,

133
00:10:59,796 --> 00:11:05,198
[SPEAKER_06]: you know, the thought process of as we move forward as this council and not having legal representation.

134
00:11:05,378 --> 00:11:13,440
[SPEAKER_06]: I don't want to ask KP law for anything, because again, we don't know what their funding mechanism is in place with the city.

135
00:11:13,460 --> 00:11:15,601
[SPEAKER_06]: We don't know what we pay and whatnot.

136
00:11:15,621 --> 00:11:25,184
[SPEAKER_06]: So I know this is important about moving our city forward, but again, I think we need the pieces in place before we make any movement on anything.

137
00:11:26,125 --> 00:11:26,925
[SPEAKER_06]: And that's right now.

138
00:11:28,227 --> 00:11:39,576
[SPEAKER_06]: from what I've seen and what we've dealt with for the last few months, especially, is not having legal representation that responds to the council and our wishes.

139
00:11:39,616 --> 00:11:43,439
[SPEAKER_06]: So I just wanted to share my concerns.

140
00:11:44,040 --> 00:11:44,340
[SPEAKER_06]: Thank you.

141
00:11:46,281 --> 00:11:46,962
[SPEAKER_12]: Councilor Scarpelli.

142
